@node intro "Introducing Whois 1.0"
@WordWrap
@{jcenter}@{bg fill} Introduction @{bg background}
@{jleft}
This is a simple whois client for the Amiga.

You can access the whois database maintened by organisations like Internic. These organisations register domain names with some informations (ie. Administrator of the network, Technical contact and so on).

With this whois client, you can retrieve and search throught this very large database easily.
@endnode

@node reqs "Requirements"
@WordWrap
@{jcenter}@{bg fill} Requirements @{bg background}
@{jleft}
To run whois you need:
@{lindent 2}
@{b}Ě@{ub} A TCP/IP stack (like Miami or AmiTCP)

@{b}Ě@{ub} An Amiga :)
@endnode

@node install "Installation"
@WordWrap
@{jcenter}@{bg fill} Installation @{bg background}
@{jleft}
Just copy the program where you want (ie. AmiTCP:bin/).
@endnode

@node usage "Usage"
@WordWrap
@{jcenter}@{bg fill} Usage @{bg background}
@{jleft}
The usage is the same as with the standard un*x Whois command.

The syntax is:
@{lindent 2}
@{b}whois [ -h host ] name@{ub}
@{lindent 0}
Where @{i}host @{ui}is the whois server you want to connect to and @{i}name @{ui}are the arguments to give to the server.

The default hostname is whois.internic.net

@{u}Example:@{uu}
@{lindent 2}
Let's say you want to get some informations about the domain nullpointer.com
You will type @{b}whois nullpointer.com@{ub} and then get informations about this domain.

Internic only handles .GOV .NET .COM .MIL and .ORG if you want to get informations about a domaine like something.fr, then try using @{b}whois -h whois.nic.fr something.fr@{ub}

You can of course search from words, like @{b}whois "Foo Bar"@{ub}
@{lindent 0}
The best thing to do is to try @{b}whois help@{ub} to get help from the server (or whois -h whois.blabla.bla help).
@endnode

